Addressed to M. Vipsanius Agrippa, Augustus* ‘Minister of War' - and greatest general ; he defeated Sextus Pompey at Naulochus, 36 B.C., and was commander at Actium, 31 B.c. Apparently Agrippa, or Agrippa's friends, had suggested to Horace that he celebrate the gen- eral's exploits in verse. This ode is Horace's skillful apology and should be compared with similar expressions, 2, 12; 4. 2, 27 ff.; S. 2, 1, 123 Epist. 2, 1, ²50 ff. In each case, however, while declaring his unfitness
